Exoplanet Characterization & Habitability Analysis

Comprehensive analysis of confirmed exoplanets from NASA Exoplanet Archive

Project Summary

This project uses data from the NASA Exoplanet Archive and TESS mission to:

  • Query and analyze confirmed exoplanet parameters
  • Download and process TESS light curves for transit detection
  • Create exploratory visualizations of planet populations
  • Perform Box Least Squares (BLS) analysis for period finding
  • Engineer physical features (insolation, equilibrium temperature)
  • Build machine learning models to classify planet types

Physical Properties

Visualizations

Radius vs Orbital Period

Shows the distribution of exoplanets in radius-period space. Color indicates equilibrium temperature. Notice the different populations: hot Jupiters (large, short period), super-Earths, and mini-Neptunes.

Mass-Radius Relationship

Demonstrates the relationship between planetary mass and radius. Rocky planets (red line) have a steeper slope than gaseous planets (blue line). Color shows density variation.

Insolation vs Radius

Shows stellar insolation (energy received) vs planet radius. The green shaded region marks the potentially habitable zone (0.25-1.5 times Earth's insolation).

BLS Periodogram

Box Least Squares periodogram for TOI-700, showing the detected orbital period from TESS light curve analysis.

Phase-Folded Light Curve

Raw and phase-folded light curve of TOI-700. The folded curve reveals the transit signature by stacking observations at the same orbital phase.

Feature Importance

Random Forest model feature importances for classifying rocky vs gaseous planets. Shows which physical parameters are most predictive.

Interactive 3D Visualization

Explore the exoplanet dataset in three dimensions! Rotate, zoom, and hover over individual planets to see their names and properties.

Data Files

All processed data has been saved in the data/ directory:

  • exoplanet_catalog.csv - Full NASA Exoplanet Archive dataset with engineered features
  • toi700_lightcurve.csv - TESS light curve data for TOI-700

Machine Learning Results

A Random Forest classifier was trained to distinguish between rocky (R < 1.6 R⊕) and gaseous (R ≥ 1.6 R⊕) planets using physical parameters:

  • Orbital period
  • Stellar insolation
  • Equilibrium temperature
  • Stellar radius
  • Stellar effective temperature

The model demonstrates that these physical properties can effectively classify planet types, with equilibrium temperature and orbital period being among the most important features.

Generated with Python using lightkurve, astroquery, scikit-learn, matplotlib, and plotly
